## Building a Calculator in Vue 3

**Mental model:** A calculator is a small state machine: `display`, stored `operand`, pending `op`, and a `fresh` flag (does the next digit start a new number?). Each button transitions this state. Modelling those four fields explicitly prevents chained-operation bugs.

### Step 1 — The four refs
```vue
<script setup>
import { ref } from 'vue';
const display = ref('0');
const operand = ref(null);
const op = ref(null);
const fresh = ref(true);
</script>
```

### Step 2 — Entering digits
```js
function digit(d) {
  display.value = fresh.value || display.value === '0' ? d : display.value + d;
  fresh.value = false;
}
```

### Step 3 — Applying an operator
Compute any pending op first so chains work.

```js
function choose(next) {
  const cur = parseFloat(display.value);
  if (op.value && !fresh.value) { const r = compute(operand.value, cur, op.value); display.value = String(r); operand.value = r; }
  else operand.value = cur;
  op.value = next; fresh.value = true;
}
```

### Step 4 — Equals / clear
```js
function equals() { if (op.value) { display.value = String(compute(operand.value, parseFloat(display.value), op.value)); op.value = null; fresh.value = true; } }
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Divide by zero | Guard → "Error". |
| Leading zeros | Replace `'0'` on first digit. |
| Chained ops | Apply pending before storing next. |

**Interview tip:** The `fresh` flag is the crux — it's the state that decides append-vs-replace right after an operator or equals, and forgetting it is the #1 calculator bug.

